---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'Building an EU-sovereign AI chatbot for my students — dev.jeroenveen.nl';
const description = 'Lessons from roughly 1,400 real student questions: GDPR as architecture, a minimal stack, why chunking beats embeddings, and the state of the European AI ecosystem.';
const publishedOn = '2026-04-21';
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <a href="#article" class="skip-nav">Skip to article</a>
  <main>
    <article class="article">
      <nav class="article-nav" aria-label="Site navigation">
        <a href="/">← dev.jeroenveen.nl</a>
      </nav>

      <header class="article-header" id="article">
        <span class="article-label">Writing</span>
        <h1 class="article-title">Building an EU-sovereign AI chatbot for my students</h1>
        <p class="article-subtitle">
          Lessons from roughly 1,400 real questions across one semester.
        </p>
        <p class="article-meta">
          <time datetime={publishedOn}>21 April 2026</time>
          <span class="sep">·</span>
          <span>~8 min read</span>
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="article-body">
        <p>
          Sometime in 2025 I decided my students should have a better way to search course
          materials than <code>Ctrl-F</code>. They study embedded machine learning — lecture notes,
          datasheets, MCU reference manuals, standards documents. A ChatGPT-style interface would
          be ideal. But every option I looked at sent their queries, their phrasing, their
          struggles, and their names to servers outside Europe.
        </p>

        <p>
          Under GDPR that's a problem. Not just student grades are personal data — every question
          a student asks is personal data about their learning. Sending all of that to a US cloud
          to get it paraphrased by a language model is a gift to whoever processes it there. So I
          built my own.
        </p>

        <p>
          A year later, two cohorts have used it, the deployment has answered roughly 1,400 real
          questions in a two-month window of the spring semester alone, and I've learned some
          things. I paid for the server myself and built the system in evenings and weekends, so
          what follows is one person's report — not a vendor pitch.
        </p>

        <figure class="article-figure">
          <img src="/screenshots/ese-bot.png" alt="ESE Bot landing screen: Your AI assistant for Embedded Machine Learning" loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>ESE Bot landing screen. Four suggested topics, one input, dark theme.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>The stack I ended up with</h2>

        <p>Every component runs within the EU:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Weaviate</strong> (Netherlands) for vector search and embedding storage</li>
          <li><strong>Mistral AI</strong> (France, GDPR-compliant inference) for the language model</li>
          <li><strong>Hetzner</strong> (Germany) for hosting, on a small VPS</li>
          <li><strong>Vue.js + FastAPI</strong>, deployed with Docker Compose, nginx in front for TLS</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          No US cloud services. No OpenAI. No Pinecone. Every component processes data within EU
          borders. The whole deployment comes up with a single <code>docker compose up</code>
          command on a cheap Hetzner box.
        </p>

        <h2>What I rejected, and why</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>LangChain.</strong> I wanted a codebase I could audit in an afternoon. Heavy
          orchestration frameworks make it easy to start and hard to understand. Direct API calls
          gave me a codebase small enough to fit in my head — and that students can read and learn
          from. This was a design decision I wrote down in an ADR so I wouldn't quietly drift back
          later.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>US-hosted LLMs of any flavor.</strong> Even when a provider offers "European
          endpoints," the data-processing chain often crosses the Atlantic for training,
          monitoring, or safety review. Mistral's commercial tier keeps the whole chain inside the
          EU and has the DPA to match. That was the cleanest path.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Managed vector databases with unclear residency.</strong> Weaviate runs as a
          container on my own server. The embeddings, the queries, the cached retrievals — all of
          it lives on the same box.
        </p>

        <h2>Four things that actually mattered</h2>

        <h3>1. A minimal stack paid for itself</h3>
        <p>
          Every dependency I avoided was a question I didn't have to answer later. When a student
          reports a weird retrieval, I can read the code end-to-end in under an hour. When
          Dependabot opens a PR, I can usually decide in minutes. When I hand this over to a
          successor, there's nothing hidden. This compounds.
        </p>

        <h3>2. GDPR compliance is an architecture decision, not a checklist</h3>
        <p>
          You can't retrofit sovereignty. If your vector database is in us-east-1, your LLM is in
          California, and your logs ship to a SaaS in Delaware, no amount of cookie banners fixes
          it. The <em>location</em> of every component is load-bearing. Choosing those components
          first — and constraining everything else around them — was the only way to get a system
          I could defend to a DPO.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Chunking strategy beats embedding model</h3>
        <p>
          I spent a lot of time benchmarking embedding models. I shouldn't have. The biggest
          retrieval quality improvements came from chunking: sentence-level splitting, preserving
          heading breadcrumbs, keeping tables intact, not letting chunks cross document
          boundaries. Once that was right, swapping embedding models made a marginal difference.
          Get the chunker right first.
        </p>

        <h3>4. The EU AI ecosystem is further along than I expected</h3>
        <p>
          A year ago I assumed I'd be making compromises. I haven't needed to. Mistral has been
          solid for the inference workload. And for future-proofing, the landscape has filled out
          considerably:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>EuroLLM</strong> — 35 EU languages, Apache 2.0, built by a European consortium</li>
          <li><strong>GPT-NL</strong> — Dutch sovereign LLM, backed by TNO and SURF</li>
          <li><strong>Salamandra</strong> — Barcelona Supercomputing Center, open weights</li>
          <li><strong>Teuken</strong> — German sovereign LLM initiative</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          These aren't curiosities. They're production-credible alternatives arriving on a 12–24
          month horizon. The argument that "there's no European option" is no longer true.
        </p>

        <h2>What the usage data shows</h2>

        <p>
          Across a two-month window in spring 2025, the system answered roughly 1,400 student
          questions. The distribution is what you'd hope for in an embedded ML course: ML concepts,
          hardware selection, model optimization, performance tradeoffs, and plenty of debugging
          questions — code the student is stuck on, a datasheet they don't understand, a shield
          they can't figure out. The bot became a patient first-line reviewer: not replacing the
          lecturer, but absorbing the questions that don't really need one.
        </p>

        <h2>Where this goes next</h2>

        <p>
          I'm now generalizing the EU-sovereign core — the retrieval layer, the GDPR-safe logging,
          the deployment pattern — for teams who need the same guarantees outside education:
          healthcare, legal, government, SMEs. Anywhere the data cannot leave Europe but the users
          still want an AI assistant. It isn't productized yet, and I'm not running a cold outbound
          campaign. If you're working on something in this space and want to compare notes, I'm
          happy to.
        </p>

        <p>
          The ESE Bot itself will stay where it is: one small server, one educator, two cohorts,
          and an experiment that became a production system somewhere along the way.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <p class="article-links">
          Repository:
          <a href="https://github.com/ducroq/ese_bot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/ducroq/ese_bot</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

